	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Review of the treatment of NTBs under (I)EPAs posted</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 October 2010
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>ICTSD has published a paper looking at the treatment of sanitary and phytosanitary (SPS) and technical barriers to trade (TBTs) under the EPAs. ‘It sets out a common vision on issues that could constitute sanitary and phytosanitary and technical barriers’ and ‘investigates how abusive use of these provisions could be an obstacle to market access.’</p><p>After a brief introduction, the paper reviews the disciplines on traditional barriers to market access under the EPAs (tariffs and quotas) before substantively exploring:</p>
<ul>

<li>the provisions on SPS and non-tariff barriers (NTBs) under the WTO and EPA agreements;</li>

<li>technical regulation and conformity assessment implementation procedures;</li>

<li>specific sanitary and phytosanitary measures;</li>

<li>the relationship between EPA rules and WTO rules on non-traditional barriers to trade.</li>

</ul>
<p>The paper notes the varying ability of companies in different ACP countries to meet SPS and technical standards, and hence their varied ability to trade effectively under the various EPAs. It is argued that SPS measures can act as an important impediment to trade. Indeed, the paper notes that ‘low-income countries have … experienced a decline in their share of world agricultural trade’ since the 1980s. The paper argues that ‘diversification of low-income country food and agricultural exports from non-traditional bulk agricultural commodities … to high value perishable products … and processed agri-food products holds potential for great gains in trade earnings, hence the importance attached to addressing SPS-related constraints on ACP exports. The importance of establishing cooperative arrangements based on the integrity of food inspection procedures is emphasised.</p><p>The paper concludes that ‘much can be done through the EPAs to considerably reduce the trade restrictive effects of how the EU frames and applies technical barriers to trade or sanitary, phytosanitary regulations and determines the compliance with them.’ It is argued that ‘EPAs could be useful tools to address the deficiencies of the WTO agreements, facilitating the implementation of provisions that are of particular interest to ACP countries.’ However, the paper concludes that on their current form, ‘EPAs fall short of their promise’ of facilitating trade by getting to grips with the increasingly important SPS barriers to trade, since they ‘neither contain detailed provisions on SPS and TBT measures nor set out procedural guidelines for operationalising key disciplines in these areas.’ The development cooperation provisions of EPAs also fall far short of requirements in terms of assisting ACP governments in getting to grips with SPS challenges.</p><p>The paper argues that ACP governments should pursue equivalence agreements on SPS standards and compliance procedures, with special technical committees being set up ‘to deal with TBT and SPS barriers to trade’. This should be backed up by ‘specific development cooperation commitments and mechanisms for their implementation’.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>ICTSD, ‘SPS and TBT in the EPAs between the EU and the ACP Countries’, August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/downloads/2010/09/prevost_web_final.pdf" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/downloads/2010/09/prevost_web_final.pdf</a></p><p>ICTSD, summary of paper ‘SPS and TBT in the EPAs between the EU and the ACP Countries’, August 2010</p><p>
<a href="http://ictsd.org/i/publications/84277/" target="_self">http://ictsd.org/i/publications/84277/</a></p><p>B. Hearn, V. Kok, J. Piesse and C. Thirtle, ‘A preliminary analysis of European assistance to agriculture in sub-Saharan Africa’, prepared for OECD, 2009</p><p>
<a href="http://workspace.imperial.ac.uk/africanagriculturaldevelopment/Public/Preliminary%20Analysis%20of%20European%20Assistance%20to%20Agriculture%20in%20SSA%20FINAL.pdf" target="_self">http://workspace.imperial.ac.uk/africanagriculturaldevelopment/Public/Pr...</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>From the perspective of ACP agricultural sectors, the potential of EPAs to assist ACP stakeholders in getting to grips with SPS standards needs to be seen against the background of recent academic analysis prepared for OECD which reveals that ‘since the 1980s bilateral aid to agriculture has halved’, with the share of DAC aid going to agriculture having fallen sharply from 17% in the late 1980s to 6% in recent years, despite a relative increase noted in recent years. In addition, support to SPS compliance and verification is a tiny proportion of this total aid, relative to the scale of the challenges faced.</p><p>Realising the potential of EPAs for facilitating trade, and helping ACP exporters to overcome obstacles posed by the stricter application of more rigorous SPS standards and emergence of more clearly articulated quality standards, would appear to hinge on the adoption of clear and comprehensive policies to address these issues in the design and application of EU standards (including support for capacity building at private- and public-sector levels in ACP countries under ‘aid for trade’ programmes). This suggests a need to establish a clear development dimension to all aspects of EU SPS, food-safety and food-quality policy, in order to meet in full the commitments made under the Cotonou agreement to ‘the progressive removal of barriers to trade between the Parties’.</p>
		</div>
		
